<img width="200" height="200" src="https://truthout.org/wp-content/uploads/2018/03/cropped-Truthout-T-logo-sq-1200x1200-e1521532408148-200x200.png" class="truthout-logo" alt="A white lower-case t on a black background" srcset="https://truthout.org/wp-content/uploads/2018/03/cropped-Truthout-T-logo-sq-1200x1200-e1521532408148-200x200.png 200w, https://truthout.org/wp-content/uploads/2018/03/cropped-Truthout-T-logo-sq-1200x1200-e1521532408148-400x400.png 400w, https://truthout.org/wp-content/uploads/2018/03/cropped-Truthout-T-logo-sq-1200x1200-e1521532408148-250x250.png 250w, https://truthout.org/wp-content/uploads/2018/03/cropped-Truthout-T-logo-sq-1200x1200-e1521532408148-270x270.png 270w, https://truthout.org/wp-content/uploads/2018/03/cropped-Truthout-T-logo-sq-1200x1200-e1521532408148-192x192.png 192w, https://truthout.org/wp-content/uploads/2018/03/cropped-Truthout-T-logo-sq-1200x1200-e1521532408148-180x180.png 180w, https://truthout.org/wp-content/uploads/2018/03/cropped-Truthout-T-logo-sq-1200x1200-e1521532408148-32x32.png 32w, https://truthout.org/wp-content/uploads/2018/03/cropped-Truthout-T-logo-sq-1200x1200-e1521532408148.png 512w" sizes="(max-width: 200px) 100vw, 200px" />
</div>
<span class="meta-label uppercase">Reading List</span>
</div>
<div class="column entry-content">
<article class="reading-list-item">
<div class='sections' style='color: #2c5b53;'>Economy &amp; Labor</div>
<a href="https://truthout.org/articles/a-big-oil-bailout-would-be-the-opposite-of-the-green-new-deal-we-need/">A Big Oil Bailout Would Be the Opposite of the Green New Deal We Need</a>
</article>
<article class="reading-list-item">
<div class='sections' style='color: #2c5b53;'>Economy &amp; Labor</div>
<a href="https://truthout.org/articles/covid-19-was-a-trigger-but-capitalism-caused-the-economic-crash/">COVID-19 Was a Trigger, But Capitalism Caused the Economic Crash</a>
</article>
<article class="reading-list-item">
<div class='sections' style='color: #0ba864;'>Environment &amp; Health</div>
<a href="https://truthout.org/articles/covid-19-may-increase-heat-extremes-this-summer/">COVID-19 May Increase Heat Extremes This Summer</a>
</article>
<article class="reading-list-item">
<div class='sections' style='color: #1958aa;'>Politics &amp; Elections</div>
<a href="https://truthout.org/articles/trumps-lies-are-killing-his-supporters-as-covid-starts-to-sweep-rural-america/">Trump&#8217;s Lies Are Killing His Supporters as COVID Starts to Sweep Rural America</a>
</article>
<article class="reading-list-item">
<div class='sections' style='color: #cc822e;'>Prisons &amp; Policing</div>
<a href="https://truthout.org/articles/where-im-incarcerated-people-with-covid-19-are-warehoused-in-a-gym/">Where I’m Incarcerated, People With COVID-19 Are Warehoused in a Gym</a>
</article>
<article class="reading-list-item">
<div class='sections' style='color: #0ba864;'>Environment &amp; Health</div>
<a href="https://truthout.org/articles/a-covid-19-vaccine-will-not-be-enough-we-need-a-plan-to-distribute-it/">A COVID-19 Vaccine Will Not Be Enough &#8212; We Need a Plan to Distribute It</a>
</article>
</div>
</aside>
</div>
<div class="entry-content primary-content-column columns small-12 medium-8">
<p>Nadina LaSpina is a long-time disability rights activist and author of the memoir, <a href="https://nyupress.org/9781613320990/"><em>Such a Pretty Girl: A Story of Struggle, Empowerment, and Disability Pride</em></a>. LaSpina contracted polio as a baby, and as a child in her native Sicily, was the frequent target of pity by those who considered her doomed to an unhappy and lonely life.</p>
<p>Arriving in the U.S. at 13, she spent most of her adolescence in hospitals undergoing painful treatments in the hope of a cure that never materialized. Against the political tumult of the &lsquo;60s, LaSpina rebelled both personally and politically. She refused to accept both the limitations placed on her by others and the dominant narrative surrounding disability. With her disabled comrades, she took to the streets to demand rights, services and respect. Together, they worked to build the disability rights movement into a global force.</p>
<p>Despite discrimination and stereotypes, LaSpina created a fulfilling life for herself as a successful professor and a tireless fighter. Still a committed activist, she also mentors young disabled women. In her memoir, she offers a much-needed insider&rsquo;s account of a struggle that continues to this day. In this interview, LaSpina discusses how her childhood influenced her to write her book and how the fight for disability justice is ongoing.</p><div class="truth-post-content-high  inline-callout-container" id="truth-255792"><aside class=" callout inline-callout callout--subscribe callout--light" id="truth-255392">
<h4>Never miss another story</h4>
<p>Get the news you want, delivered to your inbox every day.</p>
